While it’s fun to hand-code bit-bang assembly routines, implementing higher level features such as fixed point math and protocol stacks is more tedious and error-prone in assembly. In order to facilitate more complicated code, I developed a C toolchain for BIO programs. These programs are compiled down into Rust assembly macros, so the final Xous OS compilation and linkage is done using pure Rust, without blobs. Developing a C methodology inside Xous is tricky, because one of the key benefits of the Xous ecosystem being pure Rust is that we don’t have to maintain any tooling. We’d like to keep it so that the only tool required to build a Xous image is stable Rust. The moment a C compiler is introduced into the build process, we have to wade through a hodge-podge of distribution-specific C toolchains, greatly increasing developer friction and maintenance burden. Our solution to this problem, at least for now, is to borrow the Zig ecosystem’s clang C compiler. Zig distributes its toolchain as a Python package, which is built on the assumption that virtually all computers already have a Python distribution of some kind. Thus, to build C code for the BIO, one uses Python to install a Zig toolchain and then uses the C compiler built into the Zig toolchain to build C code: First, users install Zig using python3 -m pip install ziglang. Only the 0.15 toolchain is compatible with the BIO scripts. Then, users compile BIO C programs into Rust assembly macros using python3 -m ziglang build -Dmodule=<your-program> inside the libs/bio-lib/src/c directory. The build script compiles C code down to a clang intermediate assembly, which is then handed off to a Python script that translates it into a Rust macro which is checked into Xous as a buildable artifact using its pure-Rust toolchain. The Python script also checks the assembly code for certain motifs that can trigger erratum in the BIO core and automatically patches them. Thus, the only time a C toolchain is needed is if a developer needs to change the C code; re-using an existing C program requires only Rust. As a side-effect, this also paves an on-ramp for Zig developers to write BIO code. Here’s an example showing what C-for-BIO looks like: // pin is provided as the GPIO number to drive
// strip is an array of u32's that contain GRB data
// len is the length of the strip
void ws2812c(uint32_t pin, uint32_t *strip, uint32_t len) { uint32_t led; // sanity check the pin value if (pin > 31) { return; } uint32_t mask = 1 << pin; uint32_t antimask = ~mask; set_gpio_mask(mask); set_output_pins(mask); // ensure timing with a nil quantum here clear_gpio_pins_n(antimask); wait_quantum(); // main loop for (uint32_t i = 0; i < len; i++) { led = strip[i]; for (uint32_t bit = 0; bit < 24; bit++) { if ((led & 0x800000) == 0) { // 2 hi set_gpio_pins(mask); wait_quantum(); wait_quantum(); // 5 lo clear_gpio_pins_n(antimask); wait_quantum(); wait_quantum(); wait_quantum(); wait_quantum(); wait_quantum(); } else { // 5 hi set_gpio_pins(mask); wait_quantum(); wait_quantum(); wait_quantum(); wait_quantum(); wait_quantum(); // 5 lo clear_gpio_pins_n(antimask); wait_quantum(); wait_quantum(); wait_quantum(); wait_quantum(); wait_quantum(); } led <<= 1; } }
} void main(void) { uint32_t pin; uint32_t actual_leds; uint32_t rate; // blocks until these are configured pin = pop_fifo1(); actual_leds = pop_fifo1(); rate = pop_fifo1(); while (1) { ws2812c(pin, led_buf, actual_leds); rainbow_update(actual_leds, rate); for (uint32_t i = 0; i < 100000; i++) { wait_quantum(); } }
} This is an example of bit-banging a WS2812C LED protocol. The source code is split between the main and header . Here, we leverage the “quantum” feature to get exact pulse timings without resorting to cycle-counting. The “quantum” is set to a period of 150 ns, which evenly divides all of the required high/low timing patterns. So long as all the computation in the loop finishes before the next quantum, the timing requirements of the WS2812C are met. The nascent C library also includes a fixed-point math library, so the demo can compute color effects in addition to driving the LED string. The whole demo program, including the fixed point math library, uses only about 25% of the BIO memory: 1062 bytes out of the 4096 available. Have a look at the “ colorwheel ” demo for code, or the README in bio-lib for a reminder on how to use the C toolchain.

