Let's walk through the Captouch object implementation as an example of how to use the API. The BIO implements captouch sensoring by measuring the rise-time of a pin based on the parasitic capacitance of the pin charging up through the built-in pull-up resistor. The core of any BIO application consists of a structure like this: pub struct Captouch { // --- common to all BIO implementations --- // The "shared state" object. Implements `BioApi`. bio_ss: Bio, // BIO implementations have between zero and four handles. Each handle is a reservation to a virtual memory // aperture that allows the host to interact with a BIO FIFO. It also tracks the lifetime of the virtual // memory page and Drops it when it goes out of scope, hence, we must store it even if we don't interact with it. _txrx_handle: CoreHandle, // CoreCsr is a convenience object that manages CSR `view` of the handle. The handle is just a memory range; // the CoreCsr gives it semantic meaning. txrx: CoreCsr, // Tracks the resources used by the object resource_grant: ResourceGrant, // --- specific to Captouch --- threshold: u32, baseline: u32,
} Two implementations are recommended for every BIO object. The first is a Resources implementation. This encodes what specific resources your BIO application expects to use. impl Resources for Captouch { fn resource_spec() -> ResourceSpec { ResourceSpec { // An ASCII name that is associated with the resource table, allowing us to track who claimed what. claimer: "Captouch".to_string(), // A Vec whose length represents the number of cores required by the BIO code. The code can be locked // to a specific core, or in this case, left as `Any` cores: vec![CoreRequirement::Any], // Which FIFOs are used in the BIO code. FIFOs are generally hard-coded into the BIO code. fifos: vec![Fifo::Fifo3], // Any static pin mappings required by the BIO code. These are pins that are defined in the static // BIO code and thus immutable static_pins: vec![], // A count of the number of dynamically allocated pins that the code will expect to use. dynamic_pin_count: 1, } }
} A Drop implementation allows the BIO object to release its resources automatically when it goes out of scope. This is boilerplate and can basically be copy-pasta between implementations. impl Drop for Captouch { fn drop(&mut self) { for &core in self.resource_grant.cores.iter() { self.bio_ss.de_init_core(core).unwrap(); } self.bio_ss.release_resources(self.resource_grant.grant_id).unwrap(); }
} Finally, there should be at least a new() implementation for the BIO object. impl Captouch { // In this example, the user specifies the dynamic pin as an `arbitrary_int::u5`, and // can also specify a mode for IO configuration. The three possible modes for IoConfig // are `Overwrite`, where any previous pin configurations are overwritten on `new()`; // `SetOnly` which will effectively "OR" in the new pin configs; and `ClearOnly` which // will clear any pin configuration where the bit is set to `1`. // // If IoConfigMode is None, the system defaults to Overwrite mode. pub fn new(pin: u5, io_mode: Option<IoConfigMode>) -> Result<Self, BioError> { // The `iox` object is the API for configuring IO pads let iox = bao1x_api::iox::IoxHal::new(); // This call translates a BIO pin into the specific (Port, pin) tuple used in // the GPIO subsystem. i.e. BIO pin 0 is PortB pin 0, BIO pin 18 is PortC pin 2, etc. let port_config = bao1x_api::bio::bio_bit_to_port_and_pin(pin); // This call is necessary to enable the Pull-ups and the Schmitt trigger on the pads. // The BIO can't configure these bits directly, hence, they are part of the `new()` routine. iox.setup_pin( port_config.0, port_config.1, Some(IoxDir::Input), Some(bao1x_api::IoxFunction::Gpio), Some(IoxEnable::Enable), Some(IoxEnable::Enable), None, None, ); // Allocates the BIO shared state interface object let mut bio_ss = Bio::new(); // Claim core resource and initialize it let resource_grant = bio_ss.claim_resources(&Self::resource_spec())?; // The main thing that CoreConfig does is set the CLockMode. See the text below on how // ClockMode works, but in this case, we're telling the system that the Quantum comes // from an external pin that is the captouch pin. let config = CoreConfig { clock_mode: bao1x_api::bio::ClockMode::ExternalPin(BioPin::new(pin.as_u8())) }; // This line initializes the core that was granted to us in the resource grant. It also // passes the actual captouch code, which is inside the `bio_code!` macro below. bio_ss.init_core(resource_grant.cores[0], captouch_sense_code(), config)?; // claim pin resource - this only claims the resource, it does not configure it // this basically sends a message to the shared BIO resource manager that we're // claiming the pin passed by the user. bio_ss.claim_dynamic_pin(pin.as_u8(), &Captouch::resource_spec().claimer)?; // Now configure the claimed resource. This actually causes the IO mux subsystem to // unmap the pin from the GPIO/AF subsystem, and dedicate it to the BIO subsystem. let mut io_config = IoConfig::default(); io_config.mapped = 1 << pin.as_u32(); io_config.mode = io_mode.unwrap_or(IoConfigMode::Overwrite); bio_ss.setup_io_config(io_config).unwrap(); // After this call, the loaded code starts running on the BIO core. bio_ss.set_core_run_state(&resource_grant, true); // The call below gets a handle to FIFO3. Again, this is a page of virtual memory that is now // owned by our process. Owning the virtual memory page means we can quickly query the FIFO // state, without having to send a message to the `bio_ss`. All the previous interactions // with the `bio_ss` incurred a syscall and message delay penalty; once the FIFO is mapped // into our memory space, we can access the FIFO by simply dereferencing a pointer. // // safety: fifo1 and fifo2 are stored in this object so they aren't Drop'd before the object is // destroyed let txrx_handle = unsafe { bio_ss.get_core_handle(Fifo::Fifo3) }?.expect("Didn't get FIFO3 handle"); // This converts the handle into an object with CSR-like semantic meanings. While not obvious // from this example, one reason handles and CSRs are split is that we can now freely create and // send handles around inside our process space. However, in this example, we just do something // very simple with it so it seems like an unnecessary extra step. let mut txrx = CoreCsr::from_handle(&txrx_handle); // Here we are using UTRA calls to access FIFO #3. We drop into the FIFO the pin number that the // captouch code is expecting. This is put in exactly once; the BIO code remembers it and continues // forward from here. txrx.csr.wo(bio_bdma::SFR_TXF3, 1 << pin.as_u32()); Ok(Self { bio_ss, txrx, // safety: tx and rx are wrapped in CSR objects whose lifetime matches that of the handles _txrx_handle: txrx_handle, resource_grant, threshold: DEFAULT_THRESHOLD, baseline: 0, }) }
} bio_code!( captouch_sense_code, CAPTOUCH_SENSE_START, CAPTOUCH_SENSE_END, "mv x5, x19", // Load pin mask into register x5. "mv x26, x5", // Set GPIO mask to our pin.
"10:", // start of sensor loop "mv x24, x5", // Configure pin as an OUTPUT. "mv x23, x0", // Drive pin LOW. "li x6, 0x100",
"20:", // wait loop for "low" settling - this can be made much shorter if needed // as it is, the sampling rate is about 236kHz, which is already quite high "addi x6, x6, -1", "bne x6, x0, 20b", "mv x7, x31", // remember aclk time "mv x25, x5", // make it an input // now, the pull-up on the pin will slowly charge the capacitance on the pin. We wait // for the rising edge to be detected and that is our captouch interval "mv x20, x0", // wait for quantum: based on EXTCLK rising edge on the configured pin "mv x8, x31", // remember aclk time // mask out core ID "li x10, 0x3FFFFFFF", // x10 is re-used in roll-over computation below "and x7, x7, x10", "and x8, x8, x10", // handle roll-over case: x7 is greater than x8 in the case of roll-over "bgtu x7, x8, 30f", "sub x9, x8, x7", // total cycles is x8 - x7 "j 40f",
"30:", // roll-over path "sub x10, x10, x7", // x10 now contains cycles from max versus start "add x9, x10, x8", // total cycles is x10 + x8 (masked) "40:", "mv x19, x9", // report the delta-t // the line below keeps us from blocking on the FIFO being full - we steal our own entry // and cause the host to read the stale value in the FIFO. "mv x0, x19", // drain the FIFO entry - host will read the "stale" empty entry "j 10b"
); Above is the minimum amount of code necessary to define a BIO function in Xous. There are more functions in the Captouch example; readers are referred to the implementation to see all the different APIs, as the focus of this section is to walk through the creation of a BIO object in Xous, and not go into the function of captouch in detail.
